result.execSummary:
The defendant Jose J Madrigal was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Jose J Madrigal in court.  Patrick D. Winter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
cab
  DOC agent also in court.
Based upon the defendant's compliance with the conditions of probation, the Court ordered that time in the House of Correction, which was ordered as a condition of probation but stayed to today's date, be stayed for use at the agent's discretion in the future.

Defendant Jose J Madrigal in court with attorney Rebecca M Coffee.  Benjamin Lindsay appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
cab
Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.  
As to counts 1 and 2:
Court sentenced the defendant to serve 9 months in the House of Correction as to count 1 and 2 months in the House of Correction as to count 2, consecutive,  with credit for 2 days served.  Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 14 months with the following conditions:
- Serve 60 days in the House of Correction; STAYED pending review.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.
- No contact with victim unless approved by the court.
- Obtain/maintain employment.
- No contact with firearms.
- Pay DV surcharge and DNA surcharge plus all other costs and surcharges; civil judgment if not paid.
- Pay supervision fees.
- Court set restitution at $2,841.77 to be paid through the Probation Department.  Any bail to apply towards the restitution and then to any costs and surcharges.
 
Received and filed: Pretrial Sentence Credit, Notice of Right to Seek Post-Conviction Relief, Memorandum of Conditions of Probation. 
Court advised defendant of penalties for violating the no contact order and due to this DV conviction s/he may never possess firearms or ammunition.
The next court date is in Branch 36.
  Probation Review Hearing scheduled for November 20, 2015 at 01:30 pm.

AS TO COUNTS 1 & 2
Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Court advised that under 48 USC Section 922(g)(9) the defendant is prohibited from possession of a firearm and/or ammunition after conviction of a misdemeanor crime of domestic violence. Parties are notified that effective August 1, 2015 this case will be reassigned per rotation to Judge Jeffrey Kremers, Branch 36 in Courthouse room 502. Received & Filed, Pretrial Incareration Credit, Letter from Wiser Choice. Case adjourned to branch 23 for Sentencing.

COUNT 2: Disorderly Conduct, Domestic Abuse Assessments, contrary to Wis. Stat. 947.01(1), 973.055(1), a class B Misdemeanor.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for August 25, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
